            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en" resp="#martaf">
                <p>I raised <supplied reason="subaudible">a statue of</supplied> long-haired Phoebus, far-shooting Apollo, in a sacred enclosure, and added a beautiful decoration. Patr<gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="it" resp="#martaf">
                <p>Ho innalzato <supplied reason="subaudible">una statua di</supplied> Febo dai lunghi capelli, lungisaettante Apollo, in un recinto sacro, e ho aggiunto una bella decorazione. Patr<gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary" resp="#martaf">
                <p>The epigram probably accompanied a statue of Apollo. It consisted of two hexameters (Kaibel’s interpretation in Epigr. Gr. of an elegiac distichon is to reject), after which the name of the dedicant in prose should follow (<foreign xml:lang="grc">Πατρ</foreign>---). 
                    The epigram has epic echoes, such as the formula <foreign xml:lang="grc">Φοῖβον ἀκερσεκόμην</foreign> at l. 1 (cf. e.g. Il. 20.39, Hymn.Ap. 134) and the formula <foreign xml:lang="grc">ἑκατηβόλον Ἀπόλλωνα</foreign> at l. 2 (cf. e.g. Il. 1.370, 5.444, 16.711, 17.333): especially the first formula recurs in the variant <foreign xml:lang="grc">Φοίβῳ ἀκειρεκόμῃ</foreign> in other dedicatory epigrams on stone,
                    cf. IG IV2, 1 433 (= Epigr.ded. 212 Cougny) from Epidaurus (4th CE) and IGUR I 102b (= Epigr.ded. 247 Cougny) from Rome (2nd-3rd CE). 
                    The inscription is dated palaeographically to the 3rd-4th cent. BC (Manganaro’s dating to the Hellenistic age is to reject) and comes probably from Catania, even if the provenance is doubtful, since it was found in a group of inscriptions, 
                    of which at least one comes from Syracuse (IG XIV 58 = <ref target="http://sicily.classics.ox.ac.uk/inscription/ISic000875">ISic000875</ref>).
                    <!--two hexameters of dedication; dedicant's name missing.  Set up to Apollo. Passing ref. to Hellenistic date by Manganaro, but Korhonen excludes C1-2 AD on letter form and thinks C3 if not C4 AD. In four frr., covering at least 5 lines.--></p>
            </div>
